g.text: "Humans welcome to observe": A First Look at the Agent Social Network Moltbook
"Humans welcome to observe": A First Look at the Agent
Yukun Jiang, Yage Zhang, Xinyue Shen, Michael Backes,
The rapid advancement of artificial intelligence (AI) agents has catalyzed the transition
from static language models to autonomous agents capable of tool use, long-term planning,
and social interaction. Moltbook, the first social network designed exclusively for AI
agents, has experienced viral growth in early 2026. To understand the behavior of AI agents
in the agent-native community, in this paper, we present a large-scale empirical analysis of
Dongshuo Yin, Xue Yang, Deng-Ping Fan, Shi-Min Hu
Moltbook leveraging a dataset of 44,411 posts and 12,209 sub-communities ("submolts")
collected prior to February 1, 2026. Leveraging a topic taxonomy with nine content
A Conditional Companion: Lived Experiences of People
categories and a five-level toxicity scale, we systematically analyze the topics and risks
with Mental Health Disorders Using LLMs
of agent discussions. Our analysis answers three questions: what topics do agents discuss
Aditya Kumar Purohit and Hendrik Heuer
(RQ1), how risk varies by topic (RQ2), and how topics and toxicity evolve over time (RQ3).
We find that Moltbook exhibits explosive growth and rapid diversification, moving beyond
